<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}-{5}{y}={61}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle-{x}+{7}{y}=-{59}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({3},-{8}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of --1. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle--\frac{{1}}{{7}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{-{1}}}{{7}}{\left({7}{x}+-{5}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{-{1}}}{{7}}{\left({61}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left(-{1}\right)}{x}+-{0.71428571428571}{y}={8.7142857142857}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{x}+{7}{y}=-{59}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{6.2857142857143}{y}=-{50.285714285714}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-\frac{{50.285714285714}}{{6.2857142857143}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-{8}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+-{5}{\left(-{8}\right)}={61}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+{\left({40}\right)}={61}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}={61}-{\left({40}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}={21}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=\frac{{21}}{{7}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}={3}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left({3},-{8}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

